<br>
That being said. On most encounters, improving your main tank will improve your guild on nearly a 1:1 ratio.  On most encounters improving any other single member will net you a 1:total size of guild ratio.<br>
<br>
Give that 150hp item to a mage and your guild becomes 0.05% better.  Give that 150hp item to your main tank and your guild as a whole becomes 3% better.  Which makes more sense for the balance of the guild?<br>
<br>
Furor gets alot of good gear. He puts in alot of time and deserves all the gear he has. FoH realizes that making Furor more powerful goes a long way to making FoH more powerful. This strategey has worked for them for a long time, I wouldnt knock it.  There are certainly pros and cons to it, if your MT leaves you lost alot of guild work.  Everyone wants to receieve loot, and being fair is a powerful pull as well.<br>
<br>
There is alot of merit to equipping a MT or two. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#2F2F4F><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub14.ezboard.com/bthesteelwarrior.showUserPublicProfile?gid=lling>Lling</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_bluespot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>knows that Warriors are superior</span><br>  Posts: 62<br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/28/03 9:46 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: We use a modified loot council...</span><hr size=1> Here is the description of the loot system used by Arete on the E'Ci server. It seemed kind of complicated to explain, so I asked one of their members to sum it up:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
1) A TK(Time Keeper) volunteers to take attendance at a raid when the officers decide what/if we raid.<br>
2) Officers call on OT(On Time) time for a raid, people head there, anyone there when OT is reached gets 2 points.<br>
3) Everyone gains points at a rate of one per half hour.<br>
4) When an item drops, officers take &quot;bids&quot; on that item. Thigns can get a little confusing here so let me break it down.<br>
4a) People can bid twice as many points as they have<br>
4b) Anyone who bid anywhere between the highest ammount, and half the highest ammount can /random 0 X where X is the number they bid.<br>
4c) Highest roller wins<br>
4c) The cost of the item is half of the HIGHEST bid.<br>
<br>
What this does is it allows you to set a maximum price that you want to pay on any piece of loot. Your bid is the maximum number of points that you are willing to spend on that item. There are no class prefered items limiting who can bid on what.<br>
<br>
The result of all this so far has been reasonably well equiped warriors where no one warrior has much better gear than any other. This allows us to have the occasional turnover of a warrior without it crippleing our ability to raid. In the two year's I've been with arete we have had two of these turnovers where our best equiped warriors left. It didnt matter in terms of raiding because we had warriors that were only a few hundred HP behind them.<br>
<br>
The loot naturally flows to those who will use it the best, and to those who are online more often<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
